WEBVTT

00:04.700 --> 00:05.048
.

00:05.092 --> 00:06.876
- Dada, hi.
[laughs]

00:06.919 --> 00:08.704
Later, Daddy!

00:09.966 --> 00:11.924
- That's from last week.

00:11.968 --> 00:14.623
- One recording doesn't prove
he's a present father.

00:14.666 --> 00:15.972
- How about 100?

00:16.016 --> 00:18.148
My client records one of these
almost every day.

00:18.192 --> 00:20.672
I've made a supercut.
The judge will love it.

00:20.716 --> 00:22.718
- You don't want to take this
before a judge.

00:22.761 --> 00:23.849
- You're right.

00:23.893 --> 00:25.155
They'll throw us
right out their chamber.

00:25.199 --> 00:27.157
The standard for grandparents
to claim custody

00:27.201 --> 00:28.680
over a willing parent
demands evidence

00:28.724 --> 00:31.161
of deprivation, addiction,
or abuse.

00:31.205 --> 00:33.033
- He fails to meet
the standard of fitness

00:33.076 --> 00:34.599
set by Barnett v. Jeffries.

00:34.643 --> 00:36.514
- Barnett?
Are you kidding me?

00:36.558 --> 00:38.299
What judge will believe
that a widower doctor

00:38.342 --> 00:39.778
who still wears
his wedding ring

00:39.822 --> 00:42.390
and sings his daughter
to sleep every night is unfit?

00:42.433 --> 00:44.348
- He is unfit.
- No.

00:44.392 --> 00:45.915
Advise your client
that Dr. Goodwin

00:45.958 --> 00:47.656
is showing
extraordinary compassion

00:47.699 --> 00:50.572
by not pursuing charges for her
reckless disruption of custody.

00:50.615 --> 00:52.182
- No, those voice recordings
are beautiful,

00:52.226 --> 00:53.531
but you only made them

00:53.575 --> 00:55.359
because you don't see Luna
for days at a time.

00:55.403 --> 00:57.448
- Dr. Goodwin has
a very important job.

00:57.492 --> 00:59.059
- Well, you could leave it.

00:59.102 --> 01:02.410
You could work fewer hours,
but you choose work over Luna

01:02.453 --> 01:04.151
at every opportunity
even when it meant

01:04.194 --> 01:05.891
sending her away for months.

01:05.935 --> 01:07.284
You work in a hospital.

01:07.328 --> 01:09.330
You've brought a child
into the middle of a plague

01:09.373 --> 01:11.375
to make yourself feel
more like a father.

01:11.419 --> 01:13.725
You were in a recovery ward
for days

01:13.769 --> 01:16.032
because you exposed yourself
to toxic chemicals.

01:16.076 --> 01:17.729
Did you stop to think
about Luna then?

01:17.773 --> 01:21.124
- I think about her
every moment of every day.

01:21.168 --> 01:22.560
About protecting her,

01:22.604 --> 01:25.085
but no one will be safe
until everyone is,

01:25.128 --> 01:26.216
So that is a lot
of people that--

01:26.260 --> 01:27.391
- You saw a room
full of poison,

01:27.435 --> 01:28.827
and you ran right in.

01:28.871 --> 01:31.787
You were thinking of Luna?

01:31.830 --> 01:33.223
You nearly orphaned her.

01:33.267 --> 01:35.007
Her mother is dead.

01:35.051 --> 01:36.705
Luna will never remember her,

01:36.748 --> 01:38.968
and if you died,
all she'd have is voice memos.

01:39.011 --> 01:42.406
The sound of some dead stranger
who loved her,

01:42.450 --> 01:45.061
just not enough
to put her first.

01:45.105 --> 01:47.585
Georgia died in your care

01:47.629 --> 01:49.718
knowing she never came first.

01:50.849 --> 01:52.416
She was our daughter.

01:52.460 --> 01:55.854
We're not letting that happen
to our granddaughter.

01:55.898 --> 01:58.814
[soft dramatic music]

01:58.857 --> 02:05.821
♪

02:09.172 --> 02:10.652
- Maybe you're right.

02:10.695 --> 02:14.743
♪

02:14.786 --> 02:16.832
Maybe she is better off
with you.

02:16.875 --> 02:23.273
♪

02:23.317 --> 02:25.057
[Claud's "Jordan"]

02:25.101 --> 02:27.103
- ♪ Spending

02:27.147 --> 02:28.148
- [sighs]

02:28.191 --> 02:29.627
- ♪ Your time with

02:29.671 --> 02:30.976
♪

02:31.020 --> 02:32.848
♪ The same friends

02:32.891 --> 02:36.199
♪

02:36.243 --> 02:39.246
♪ How do I reach you, baby

02:39.289 --> 02:42.031
♪ I've been thinking lately

02:42.074 --> 02:46.296
♪ That you're
too good for me ♪

02:46.340 --> 02:47.993
♪

02:48.037 --> 02:51.127
♪ How do I tell you,
darling ♪

02:51.171 --> 02:54.043
♪ I've been underwater

02:54.086 --> 02:55.653
♪

02:55.697 --> 02:58.395
♪ I can't breathe

02:58.439 --> 03:00.919
♪

03:00.963 --> 03:04.836
- What are you doing?
- Oh, um, I'm--

03:04.880 --> 03:07.665
- Looking at my stuff.
- Mina, I am so sorry.

03:07.709 --> 03:09.493
I was putting
the laundry away, and--

03:09.537 --> 03:12.583
- That's fine,
but I need to work now.

03:12.627 --> 03:15.543
College applications.
- Oh.

03:17.936 --> 03:20.243
I didn't know
that you were applying early.

03:20.287 --> 03:22.202
I have friends at NYU.
Sarah Lawrence and--

03:22.245 --> 03:25.205
- No, no, it's fine.
- Are you sure?

03:25.248 --> 03:28.817
- I'm not staying in New York,
probably not even the country.

03:32.081 --> 03:33.648
- Well, I went to Cambridge.

03:33.691 --> 03:35.127
Maybe I can write you
a letter of...

03:35.171 --> 03:36.216
- No.
- Recommendation.

03:37.391 --> 03:38.740
Thank you.

03:43.440 --> 03:45.225
[thermometer beeps]
- Here.

03:46.443 --> 03:48.228
[sighs]
You still have a fever, babe.

03:48.271 --> 03:49.359
- Oh.

03:49.403 --> 03:51.840
I can't stay home
again today.

03:51.883 --> 03:53.885
There's too many people
that need my help.

03:53.929 --> 03:56.975
- And they'll still need
your help tomorrow.

03:57.019 --> 03:58.368
Be grateful it's just the flu.

03:58.412 --> 04:02.024
Ah, so I'm gonna
drop the kids off at my mom's,

04:02.067 --> 04:03.330
and then I'll
be down in my office.

04:03.373 --> 04:04.418
You want anything?

04:04.461 --> 04:06.246
- Yeah,
a stronger immune system.

04:06.289 --> 04:09.510
[soft dramatic music]

04:09.553 --> 04:11.686
[upbeat music]

04:11.729 --> 04:13.775
- I need a full workup
in an hour.

04:13.818 --> 04:15.080
♪

04:15.124 --> 04:16.299
- I need your advice,

04:16.343 --> 04:18.170
but you can't make
any of it about you.

04:18.214 --> 04:19.520
- Only you would ask
for a favor

04:19.563 --> 04:21.086
by opening with an insult.

04:21.130 --> 04:22.914
- There's this woman
I've been spending time with,

04:22.958 --> 04:26.178
a coworker, and it's become
a bit of a situation.

04:26.222 --> 04:27.963
- Please,
half my ED is sleeping

04:28.006 --> 04:29.704
with at least one other person
in the building.

04:29.747 --> 04:31.096
It's fine.

04:31.140 --> 04:34.317
- She's married.
- Oh.

04:34.361 --> 04:36.276
- It's an open marriage.
- Dr. Bloom?

04:36.319 --> 04:39.757
- Not now.
You come.

04:39.801 --> 04:42.934
♪

04:42.978 --> 04:44.936
Okay, go.

04:46.982 --> 04:48.592
- I don't know
how it got to this.

04:48.636 --> 04:51.378
Our chemistry's insane.
- Yeah?

04:52.292 --> 04:54.903
- And honestly, I just
can't stop thinking about her.

04:54.946 --> 04:56.644
Now, I'm not down
for the polyamorous thing,

04:56.687 --> 04:58.689
but it feels kind of weird

04:58.733 --> 05:02.040
hanging out as friends
with this secret attraction.

05:02.084 --> 05:03.564
- Well, it's not a secret.

05:03.607 --> 05:06.436
It's keeping something
complicated to yourself

05:06.480 --> 05:07.959
to protect the other person.

05:08.003 --> 05:11.223
- Well, can't do that,
and I'm seeing her tonight,

05:11.267 --> 05:13.138
so please tell me
how to end it

05:13.182 --> 05:15.793
before I fall off this cliff
and somebody gets hurt.

05:15.837 --> 05:18.883
- Huh,
why does this sound familiar?

05:18.927 --> 05:21.016
- I knew it.
- Right, right,

05:21.059 --> 05:23.671
because it's exactly
what you did with us.

05:23.714 --> 05:26.717
You start something
that you've already decided

05:26.761 --> 05:29.416
doesn't have a future,
so even though it's great,

05:29.459 --> 05:30.721
you're gonna torch it.

05:30.765 --> 05:32.636
- Well, because it's not
what I wanted.

05:32.680 --> 05:34.421
Look, I never wavered on that--

05:34.464 --> 05:36.379
a traditional marriage,
a Black family.

05:36.423 --> 05:37.728
- Yet you let Evie go.

05:37.772 --> 05:39.208
[soft dramatic music]

05:39.251 --> 05:42.342
Look, Floyd, I know that you
like to think of yourself

05:42.385 --> 05:44.387
as this man who walks the path,

05:44.431 --> 05:45.954
but you keep ending up
on the cliffs.

05:45.997 --> 05:48.391
- Incoming.
- I don't know.

05:48.435 --> 05:50.350
Maybe it's because
you really want to jump.

05:50.393 --> 05:56.356
♪

05:56.399 --> 05:58.706
- Five-year-old Kiri Almeida.
Status: post heart transplant.

05:58.749 --> 06:00.664
Increasing shortness of breath.
Pulse--

06:00.708 --> 06:02.187
- She's got
a congenital heart defect.

06:02.231 --> 06:04.407
Had four heart surgeries
and a transplant last year.

06:04.451 --> 06:06.278
- They have her file.
You can read everything.

06:06.322 --> 06:08.193
- Hey, Dr. Reynolds.
- Ted, Madeline, what happened?

06:08.237 --> 06:09.847
- Kiri can't breathe.

06:09.891 --> 06:13.460
- Oh, Kir, I thought we agreed,
no more emergencies.

06:13.503 --> 06:15.679
- Let's type and cross.
- Well, she's AB.

06:15.723 --> 06:17.420
Kiri's been my patient
since she was born.

06:17.464 --> 06:19.422
- Well, could she be
rejecting the heart?

06:19.466 --> 06:20.597
- I have to do a biopsy.

06:20.641 --> 06:22.686
- But could she?
- Yes.

06:22.730 --> 06:24.122
The question is how badly.

06:24.166 --> 06:26.864
Book an OR and page Dr. Sharpe
for a biopsy.

06:26.908 --> 06:28.692
- 80-year-old man
found in St. Vartan's Park

06:28.736 --> 06:30.041
with extremely high blood sugar

06:30.085 --> 06:31.478
and altered
sense of consciousness.

06:31.521 --> 06:33.131
Alert and oriented times zero.

06:33.175 --> 06:36.657
- Sir, can you hear me?
- [groans softly]

06:36.700 --> 06:39.573
- Okay, let's run a chem 7,
CBC with diff,

06:39.616 --> 06:41.270
and let's get
a blood tox screen stat.

06:41.313 --> 06:43.968
- Got it.
- And who is next?

06:45.013 --> 06:47.058
- She's had
so many risky surgeries.

06:47.102 --> 06:49.713
- Yeah,
it's all standard protocol.

06:49.757 --> 06:54.283
- I know, but for a child?
- Extracting heart sample now.

06:54.326 --> 07:00.811
♪

07:00.855 --> 07:02.465
Prepare to withdraw
the catheter.

07:02.509 --> 07:04.032
- Yes, Dr. Reynolds.

07:04.075 --> 07:06.469
Heart rate holding steady
at 75 BPM.

07:06.513 --> 07:09.994
♪

07:10.038 --> 07:12.127
- What's the severity
of the rejection?

07:12.170 --> 07:13.563
It's 2R? 3R?

07:13.607 --> 07:15.739
- Ox at 95.

07:15.783 --> 07:18.002
- Dopamine and vasopressin
all 4.

07:18.046 --> 07:19.526
- Zero.

07:20.570 --> 07:22.877
- Zero?

07:22.920 --> 07:25.401
- There's no evidence
that she's rejecting the heart.

07:25.445 --> 07:27.882
♪

07:27.925 --> 07:29.623
- Then what the hell's
causing her symptoms?

07:29.666 --> 07:34.497
♪

07:34.541 --> 07:37.369
- Tox screen's crazy.
- Is that dioxin?

07:37.413 --> 07:39.328
Who gets poisoned with dioxin?

07:39.371 --> 07:42.331
- Dioxin poisoning
was a favorite of the KGB.

07:42.374 --> 07:43.637
- Yeah, didn't we agree

07:43.680 --> 07:45.813
that we'd leave
our nerd interests at home?

07:45.856 --> 07:47.597
- Oh, Cold War era spy craft
is the opposite of nerdy.

07:47.641 --> 07:48.946
It's awesome.

07:48.990 --> 07:51.427
- And the Cold War
is also, you know, over.

07:51.471 --> 07:53.821
- Yeah, but the KGB players
didn't just disappear.

07:53.864 --> 07:55.779
Man, everyone knows
that they're the guys

07:55.823 --> 07:57.868
who poisoned
Viktor Yushchenko in 2004.

07:57.912 --> 07:59.609
- And now I'm worried
that you're serious.

07:59.653 --> 08:03.308
This man is our patient,
not a Russian spy.

08:03.352 --> 08:07.182
- [mumbling in Russian]

08:07.225 --> 08:10.577
♪

08:10.620 --> 08:12.361
[mumbling in Russian]

08:12.404 --> 08:13.493
- Sounds like Russian to me.

08:13.536 --> 08:15.233
♪

08:21.588 --> 08:23.328
- [clears throat]

08:23.372 --> 08:24.895
Reed?

08:24.939 --> 08:26.506
- Max.

08:26.549 --> 08:28.333
- Please don't tell me that
we're short on vaccines again.

08:28.377 --> 08:31.336
I can't take that today.
- No, no, we have the vaccines.

08:31.380 --> 08:33.208
Problem is,
they've been thawing all night.

08:33.251 --> 08:34.644
This freezer's dead.

08:35.645 --> 08:37.429
- How many are in there?
- 1,000.

08:37.473 --> 08:41.433
We're gonna have to toss 'em.
- Toss 1,000 vaccines?

08:41.477 --> 08:42.696
- Unless you have a Ferrari

08:42.739 --> 08:44.045
and plan on delivering them
door-to-door.

08:44.088 --> 08:45.350
[upbeat music]

08:45.394 --> 08:48.571
Max!
That was a joke!

08:48.615 --> 08:49.833
Max.

08:49.877 --> 08:51.661
- We are not tossing
1,000 vaccines.

08:51.705 --> 08:53.097
Too many people
still need them.

08:53.141 --> 08:54.229
We need to make it safe
for everyone.

08:54.272 --> 08:55.665
- I'm sure we'll get
some walk-ins.

08:55.709 --> 08:57.798
- Take 'em to the prison ward.
- Vaccinated.

08:57.841 --> 08:59.060
- Homeless clinic
across the street.

08:59.103 --> 08:59.843
- Vaccinated.

08:59.887 --> 09:01.105
Everyone in our system

09:01.149 --> 09:02.193
who's wanted the shot
has gotten it.

09:02.237 --> 09:04.369
[phone buzzing]

09:04.413 --> 09:06.589
Max, that's good news.

09:06.633 --> 09:10.767
- Uh, when do they expire?
- Six hours.

09:10.811 --> 09:13.291
- Okay, now, that's good.
- No, that's actually bad.

09:13.335 --> 09:14.466
- Not if we move quickly.

09:14.510 --> 09:16.381
I will post
on the hospital's website.

09:16.425 --> 09:17.644
You hit up social media.

09:17.687 --> 09:19.254
If we've got six hours
to give out 1,000 shots,

09:19.297 --> 09:21.299
then let's get
1,000 people in here now.

09:29.438 --> 09:31.135
- [sighs]

09:31.179 --> 09:32.093
Thank you.

09:35.096 --> 09:36.053
[sighs]

09:40.275 --> 09:41.624
Oh.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.323
The kids make it
to your mom's okay?

09:45.367 --> 09:48.892
[eerie music]

09:48.936 --> 09:50.328
- Please don't be mad.

09:50.372 --> 09:53.897
♪

09:56.378 --> 09:56.596
.

09:56.639 --> 09:58.206
- That's the sashimi salad.

09:58.249 --> 10:00.034
Here's your octopus roll.

10:00.077 --> 10:03.037
[upbeat music]

10:03.080 --> 10:07.215
♪

10:07.258 --> 10:09.217
- Reed.
- Hmm.

10:09.260 --> 10:11.611
- What is this?
- Great response.

10:11.654 --> 10:13.221
We've already administered
50 doses,

10:13.264 --> 10:14.396
and the line's growing.

10:14.439 --> 10:15.615
- Most of these people
look like

10:15.658 --> 10:17.094
they just stepped out
of a country club.

10:17.138 --> 10:19.836
I literally saw a guy
checking his stock portfolio.

10:19.880 --> 10:21.533
No, it's wrong, okay?

10:21.577 --> 10:23.231
We need to get this vaccine

10:23.274 --> 10:25.233
to the people
who need it the most,

10:25.276 --> 10:26.843
the ones
who don't have access to it.

10:26.887 --> 10:28.715
This isn't our patient base.

10:28.758 --> 10:30.455
- Our patient base
can't just leave their jobs

10:30.499 --> 10:31.674
because they got an email.

10:31.718 --> 10:33.328
Our patient base
probably isn't on Twitter.

10:33.371 --> 10:36.374
[soft dramatic music]

10:36.418 --> 10:38.594
- I am so sorry, Reed.
- Why?

10:38.638 --> 10:40.552
- Because you're gonna have to
apologize to all these people.

10:40.596 --> 10:42.206
- Why am I gonna
to have to apologize?

10:42.250 --> 10:44.644
- Because I'm taking
these vaccines.

10:44.687 --> 10:46.036
- Come on, man.

10:46.080 --> 10:49.083
[upbeat music]

10:49.126 --> 10:51.694
Max,
what you're doing right now

10:51.738 --> 10:53.000
seems kind of crazy.

10:53.043 --> 10:54.697
- We need to get this vaccine
to the people

10:54.741 --> 10:56.830
who can't come
to the hospital or won't,

10:56.873 --> 10:59.136
to the holdouts
and to the communities

10:59.180 --> 11:00.921
who are literally dying
at twice the rate

11:00.964 --> 11:02.400
because they're being
vaccinated at half the pace.

11:02.444 --> 11:03.358
- But the people
who showed up--

11:03.401 --> 11:04.751
- Can be rescheduled.

11:04.794 --> 11:06.274
If they can show up
at a moment's notice today,

11:06.317 --> 11:08.232
they'll have no problem
showing up tomorrow.

11:08.276 --> 11:09.625
- Please don't do this.

11:09.669 --> 11:12.280
- Reed, no one is safe
until everyone is safe.

11:12.323 --> 11:14.108
These vaccines expire
in six hours.

11:14.151 --> 11:15.718
- Four.

11:15.762 --> 11:17.764
♪

11:17.807 --> 11:21.158
- How are we feeling,
Mr. Osheyevsky?

11:21.202 --> 11:24.466
- Leave me alone.
- Look, I have to ask.

11:24.509 --> 11:27.208
Do you have any idea
how something as toxic

11:27.251 --> 11:29.558
as dioxin ended up
in your bloodstream?

11:31.125 --> 11:33.736
- They want me dead.

11:33.780 --> 11:36.696
[dramatic music]

11:36.739 --> 11:40.351
♪

11:40.395 --> 11:43.267
- Who wants you dead,
Mr. Osheyevsky?

11:43.311 --> 11:45.487
- Dr. Bloom?
Mr. Osheyevsky's son is here.

11:45.530 --> 11:47.968
- Okay.
- I don't have a son.

11:48.011 --> 11:50.971
♪

11:51.014 --> 11:52.842
- Dr. Mendez to ER 1.

11:52.886 --> 11:54.496
- Okay.

11:54.539 --> 11:59.240
Uh, have Mr. Osheyevsky's
visitor tested,

11:59.283 --> 12:00.807
and I will meet him
in the waiting area.

12:00.850 --> 12:02.243
- Will do, Dr. Bloom.

12:02.286 --> 12:05.159
- Casey, move Mr. Osheyevsky
to the procedure room.

12:05.202 --> 12:08.510
Close the blinds and stay
with him until further notice.

12:08.553 --> 12:10.991
- You think he's in danger?
- Just as a precaution.

12:11.034 --> 12:14.081
♪

12:14.124 --> 12:15.604
- Sweet.

12:16.823 --> 12:18.259
- Oh, the exhibit
sounds exceptional.

12:18.302 --> 12:19.695
- It is.

12:19.739 --> 12:21.523
I love Magritte anyway,
but the Briton stuff--

12:21.566 --> 12:24.395
- Sorry.
I'll wait in your office?

12:24.439 --> 12:27.007
- No, no, no, no, no, no,
Mina, come join us.

12:27.050 --> 12:28.530
This is Alex Dorsett.

12:28.573 --> 12:29.792
She's on our board
at the hospital.

12:29.836 --> 12:31.054
- Hello, Mina.

12:31.098 --> 12:32.447
Your aunt's been telling me
all about you.

12:32.490 --> 12:34.101
- As I mentioned,
Alex is on our board,

12:34.144 --> 12:36.625
but she also happens to be
the undergraduate dean

12:36.668 --> 12:38.540
of Columbia University.

12:38.583 --> 12:41.717
[soft dramatic music]

12:41.761 --> 12:43.719
♪

12:43.763 --> 12:46.766
M--um, s--

12:46.809 --> 12:48.028
Mina?

12:48.071 --> 12:49.159
- I told you
I wasn't staying in New York.

12:49.203 --> 12:50.204
- Yeah, it doesn't hurt
just to--

12:50.247 --> 12:51.161
- You invited me here
for lunch.

12:51.205 --> 12:52.772
This is an ambush.

12:52.815 --> 12:54.077
- No, this is me caring about
you and wanting to help you.

12:54.121 --> 12:55.339
- I already told you
I don't want your help.

12:55.383 --> 12:56.732
- No, you told me

12:56.776 --> 12:58.168
that you don't want me
writing you a letter.

12:58.212 --> 12:59.430
- Because letters are supposed
to come from people

12:59.474 --> 13:00.736
who know you.

13:00.780 --> 13:03.043
You obviously
don't know me at all.

13:03.086 --> 13:07.351
♪

13:07.395 --> 13:08.613
- [sighs]

13:08.657 --> 13:10.354
- Well, Kiri's chest X-ray

13:10.398 --> 13:12.748
and CT scans
aren't what I hoped for.

13:12.792 --> 13:14.924
Her lungs seem to be failing.
- Why?

13:14.968 --> 13:16.447
- I don't know yet,
but we started her

13:16.491 --> 13:18.710
on a cocktail of antibiotics
to help fight infection.

13:18.754 --> 13:20.016
- At least she's
not rejecting the heart.

13:20.060 --> 13:21.496
- That's your takeaway?

13:21.539 --> 13:23.237
- Just trying to find something
to hold on to, Ted.

13:23.280 --> 13:25.239
- [retches]
- Kiri.

13:25.282 --> 13:26.893
- Honey.
- I'm sorry.

13:26.936 --> 13:28.938
- Oh, it's okay, baby.
- [retches]

13:28.982 --> 13:30.113
- Oh.
- Floyd?

13:30.157 --> 13:31.854
- Excuse me.

13:31.898 --> 13:34.204
Kiri, does this hurt?

13:34.248 --> 13:36.903
♪

13:36.946 --> 13:38.818
Okay, just relax.

13:38.861 --> 13:39.862
♪

13:39.906 --> 13:42.082
- It's okay.
- What's happening?

13:42.125 --> 13:44.562
♪

13:44.606 --> 13:46.434
- Her liver is failing
as well.

13:46.477 --> 13:52.483
♪

13:52.527 --> 13:54.703
- I went to the hospital
to see you,

13:54.746 --> 13:57.967
but I found out you were sick,
and I got scared

13:58.011 --> 14:00.056
because I really need
to talk to you.

14:01.579 --> 14:03.364
- You need to talk
to me about what?

14:03.407 --> 14:04.713
- This.

14:07.672 --> 14:10.458
A restraining order's
pretty harsh, Dr. Frome.

14:10.501 --> 14:13.113
- And you're violating it
right now...

14:13.156 --> 14:15.028
[eerie music]

14:15.071 --> 14:16.856
And you need to leave.

14:16.899 --> 14:19.336
- But...

14:19.380 --> 14:20.816
but don't you want me
to get better?

14:20.860 --> 14:22.992
- Of course
I want you to get better.

14:23.036 --> 14:28.215
♪

14:28.258 --> 14:30.347
But I can't help you.

14:34.699 --> 14:36.353
And you need
to leave right now,

14:36.397 --> 14:37.485
or I will call the police.

14:37.528 --> 14:39.095
- Sit down!

14:39.139 --> 14:40.531
[grunts]

14:40.575 --> 14:43.404
[phone thudding]

14:43.447 --> 14:44.971
You're gonna help me.

14:45.014 --> 14:47.974
Dr. Frome,
I need you to help me.

14:48.017 --> 14:49.976
♪

14:50.019 --> 14:52.674
I'm not better.

14:52.717 --> 14:55.329
You promised I'd get better,
but you lied.

14:55.372 --> 14:57.984
- Chance, please.
- My father lied too.

14:58.027 --> 15:00.595
♪

15:00.638 --> 15:03.554
He said he wouldn't hurt me,

15:03.598 --> 15:06.470
but...he did.

15:07.863 --> 15:11.345
And when I cried,
he called me weak

15:11.388 --> 15:13.956
and damaged goods,

15:14.000 --> 15:16.002
and...

15:16.045 --> 15:18.918
no one in the house
would help me.

15:20.571 --> 15:24.314
No one,
which is why I did what I did.

15:24.358 --> 15:29.841
♪

15:29.885 --> 15:33.497
- Chance,
your family died in a fire...

15:33.541 --> 15:35.586
that you set by accident.

15:35.630 --> 15:42.767
♪

15:46.423 --> 15:46.641
.

15:46.684 --> 15:47.990
[funky music]

15:48.034 --> 15:49.426
- Guys, I'm telling you,

15:49.470 --> 15:50.906
this vaccine
is so worth it, okay?

15:50.950 --> 15:51.994
- We don't even know
who you are.

15:52.038 --> 15:53.169
- Sorry, I told you

15:53.213 --> 15:54.605
I'm the medical director
at New Amsterdam.

15:54.649 --> 15:56.129
- New Amsterdam?
- Yeah.

15:56.172 --> 15:57.913
- You guys tried to sue me
when I was late on my bill.

15:57.957 --> 16:00.002
- No, no,
we don't do that anymore.

16:00.046 --> 16:03.484
- Tuskegee,
Henrietta Lacks, antebellum.

16:03.527 --> 16:05.529
- You've had a lifetime
to earn my trust,

16:05.573 --> 16:08.054
and you never even tried.
Why should I trust you now?

16:08.097 --> 16:09.533
- Sickle cell anemia
screenings,

16:09.577 --> 16:12.232
forced sterilization,
night doctors.

16:12.275 --> 16:13.885
- So you want to give me
one shot now,

16:13.929 --> 16:15.191
another in four weeks,

16:15.235 --> 16:17.193
and then I got to come back in
for a booster?

16:17.237 --> 16:19.500
- I got no money.
I got no house.

16:19.543 --> 16:23.156
All I got is a history
of you killing us,

16:23.199 --> 16:24.809
and I still got the vaccine.

16:24.853 --> 16:26.333
- Wait?
You did?

16:26.376 --> 16:29.205
- I don't trust you,
but I trust the science.

16:29.249 --> 16:31.207
I got the shot last month.

16:31.251 --> 16:33.905
- Save your breath.
I'm already vaccinated.

16:33.949 --> 16:34.994
- Even though you sued me,

16:35.037 --> 16:37.039
I still got the vaccine
from you.

16:37.083 --> 16:39.085
- I hear there are soldiers
refusing the shot.

16:39.128 --> 16:40.521
- I hear there's
doctors and nurses

16:40.564 --> 16:42.566
that don't want the vaccine.
- Heard that too.

16:42.610 --> 16:44.307
- If you're looking
for holdouts,

16:44.351 --> 16:46.092
you should check
your own backyard.

16:46.135 --> 16:49.051
♪

16:49.095 --> 16:52.011
- Ben Osheyevsky?
- Yes, hi.

16:52.054 --> 16:53.751
- Hi.
- How's my father?

16:53.795 --> 16:56.406
- Can I see some ID?

16:56.450 --> 16:57.886
- Of course.

16:58.669 --> 17:01.977
Oh, I must have left
my wallet in the car.

17:02.021 --> 17:03.326
My wife couldn't find
a parking spot,

17:03.370 --> 17:05.067
so I just hopped out and ran.

17:05.111 --> 17:06.677
Is he okay?

17:06.721 --> 17:08.114
♪

17:08.157 --> 17:09.680
- I need to see some ID.

17:09.724 --> 17:11.073
♪

17:11.117 --> 17:13.206
I need to confirm
that you're family.

17:13.249 --> 17:15.121
- Well, who else would I be?

17:16.861 --> 17:19.168
- How did you know
that your father was here?

17:19.212 --> 17:21.953
- I called every hospital
in the city.

17:21.997 --> 17:25.348
♪

17:25.392 --> 17:27.742
- Well, my patient is saying
that he doesn't have a son.

17:30.701 --> 17:33.182
- Well, he does.

17:33.226 --> 17:36.403
- Ben, I had to park
four blocks away,

17:36.446 --> 17:39.101
and the meter was broken,
and then I had to get tested.

17:39.145 --> 17:40.189
You left your wallet.

17:40.233 --> 17:47.327
♪

17:50.808 --> 17:52.506
You thought his dad was a spy?

17:53.855 --> 17:55.770
- I know it sounds crazy,

17:55.813 --> 17:58.294
but, well,
he said he didn't have a son,

17:58.338 --> 18:00.470
and while I don't usually

18:00.514 --> 18:03.125
suspect my patients
of espionage,

18:03.169 --> 18:05.214
this particular drug--

18:05.258 --> 18:09.175
- How was he poisoned?
- We don't know yet.

18:09.218 --> 18:11.307
- My father was a tailor
who spent 50 years

18:11.351 --> 18:13.483
in the garment district.
We hardly ever saw him.

18:13.527 --> 18:14.876
If he was a spy,

18:14.919 --> 18:17.357
at least we might have had
some cool stories.

18:18.227 --> 18:19.663
I know he's upset

18:19.707 --> 18:22.144
because we've been
looking into homes for him,

18:22.188 --> 18:24.190
but he's never
wandered off before.

18:30.152 --> 18:32.850
♪

18:32.894 --> 18:34.025
Where is he?

18:34.069 --> 18:36.289
- Uh, just give me a second.

18:36.332 --> 18:38.291
[line trills]

18:38.334 --> 18:41.511
[phone ringing]

18:41.555 --> 18:48.475
♪

18:55.743 --> 18:56.657
- What?

19:00.182 --> 19:01.749
- First her lungs,
then her liver,

19:01.792 --> 19:03.664
now her kidneys.
- Yeah.

19:03.707 --> 19:05.492
I don't want to put Kiri
through any more operations,

19:05.535 --> 19:07.058
but that may be
our only option.

19:07.102 --> 19:09.191
- Will she at least be on
the top of the transplant list?

19:09.235 --> 19:11.150
- How many more surgeries
can she take?

19:11.193 --> 19:12.412
- What do you want to do?
Nothing?

19:12.455 --> 19:15.110
- Okay, guys, can we--
can we go outside?

19:21.595 --> 19:22.944
- I just want to make a plan.

19:22.987 --> 19:25.164
- And I don't want her
to be in any more pain.

19:25.207 --> 19:27.775
- Our daughter
is going to die, Ted.

19:27.818 --> 19:29.255
- Guys, guys.

19:30.299 --> 19:32.083
The only thing
that's gonna get you

19:32.127 --> 19:33.911
through this again
is each other.

19:33.955 --> 19:36.087
- Dr. Malloy, call 247.

19:36.131 --> 19:37.915
[soft dramatic music]

19:37.959 --> 19:39.917
- We're separated.

19:39.961 --> 19:41.223
♪

19:41.267 --> 19:42.398
Five months now.

19:42.442 --> 19:44.008
- Ironic, isn't it?

19:44.052 --> 19:45.967
The first minute that Kiri
doesn't have any problems,

19:46.010 --> 19:48.099
we find out that we do.

19:48.143 --> 19:50.754
- Excuse me.
Sorry.

19:50.798 --> 19:53.061
Dr. Reynolds,
can I have a word, please?

19:53.104 --> 19:58.762
♪

19:58.806 --> 20:00.242
- Please tell me
you have good news.

20:00.286 --> 20:01.765
♪

20:01.809 --> 20:04.333
- Our request to put Kiri
on the transplant list

20:04.377 --> 20:06.683
has been rejected.

20:06.727 --> 20:07.641
- [sighs]

20:07.684 --> 20:09.469
- With multiple organ failures,

20:09.512 --> 20:12.254
they don't see her
as a viable candidate.

20:12.298 --> 20:16.519
♪

20:16.563 --> 20:19.087
How are they holding up?
- They're not.

20:19.130 --> 20:21.742
♪

20:21.785 --> 20:24.353
They've been
through so much together.

20:24.397 --> 20:27.835
I mean, I really thought
nothing could break them.

20:29.489 --> 20:31.317
They had the perfect family.

20:31.360 --> 20:33.449
♪

20:33.493 --> 20:35.146
- There's no such thing.

20:35.190 --> 20:42.328
♪

20:44.025 --> 20:47.202
- So your dad hurt you.

20:47.246 --> 20:49.117
You said that he called you
"damaged goods"?

20:49.160 --> 20:56.255
♪

21:00.346 --> 21:02.304
Chance, I can barely
get to the bathroom.

21:02.348 --> 21:05.176
I'm not--I'm not
gonna run anywhere.

21:05.220 --> 21:06.830
♪

21:06.874 --> 21:09.355
You asked me
if I want you to get better.

21:10.443 --> 21:12.227
I do.
I really do.

21:12.271 --> 21:15.317
Um, you need to help me.
You need to--

21:15.361 --> 21:19.669
- My whole family
knew what he was doing...

21:19.713 --> 21:23.325
♪

21:23.369 --> 21:26.502
But they still let it happen.

21:29.200 --> 21:31.942
So...

21:31.986 --> 21:34.728
I shouldn't feel guilty
for what I did, but--

21:34.771 --> 21:36.686
♪

21:36.730 --> 21:39.080
- I get it.
- No, no, you don't.

21:39.123 --> 21:40.168
You can't!
- I do.

21:40.211 --> 21:41.387
- How?
How?

21:41.430 --> 21:43.040
How can you know
what this feels like?

21:43.084 --> 21:45.347
- Because...

21:45.391 --> 21:46.870
I killed someone too.

21:46.914 --> 21:53.268
♪

21:56.184 --> 21:56.358
.

21:56.402 --> 21:58.926
- I fully support
the vaccine effort.

21:58.969 --> 22:01.494
I think Operation Warp Speed
has been a tremendous success.

22:01.537 --> 22:03.234
- Thank God.
I thought you were gonna say--

22:03.278 --> 22:07.674
- Personally, I didn't get it.
- No, Todd, why?

22:07.717 --> 22:09.023
- I've chosen to wait.
- Till when?

22:09.066 --> 22:10.677
Everyone you know
is dead or dying?

22:10.720 --> 22:12.026
- May I speak freely?
- Of course.

22:12.069 --> 22:14.071
- Without your
liberal condescension?

22:14.115 --> 22:15.725
- Maybe.

22:15.769 --> 22:17.945
- I have
no underlying health issues.

22:17.988 --> 22:20.469
I've been fortunate
to primarily work from home,

22:20.513 --> 22:22.689
so I've decided to wait
till the end of the line.

22:22.732 --> 22:24.386
- But this is
the end of the line.

22:24.430 --> 22:26.997
Millions of people have
already been safely vaccinated.

22:27.041 --> 22:29.130
To keep waiting now
would just be insane.

22:29.173 --> 22:30.349
It would be crazy.
It would be--

22:30.392 --> 22:31.611
I'm sorry.
I tried.

22:31.654 --> 22:33.134
- Whatever happened
to my body, my choice?

22:33.177 --> 22:34.527
- Well,
it's not just your body.

22:34.570 --> 22:37.268
Not getting the vaccine
could hurt someone else--

22:37.312 --> 22:38.835
my daughter.

22:38.879 --> 22:40.446
- Fair point.
- Really?

22:40.489 --> 22:43.710
- Sure, I'm pretty open-minded,
unlike some people I know.

22:43.753 --> 22:46.234
- Fair point.
- Look.

22:46.277 --> 22:48.236
All I'm saying is
that a lot of the conservatives

22:48.279 --> 22:50.412
that I work with
still have questions.

22:50.456 --> 22:52.458
- Conservatives are here
in this hospital?

22:52.501 --> 22:53.894
- I hate to burst your bubble.

22:53.937 --> 22:56.679
- Unvaccinated?
- Some.

22:56.723 --> 22:57.941
- Who?

22:57.985 --> 22:59.552
- Are you asking me
to name names?

22:59.595 --> 23:01.075
- No, uh--no, Todd.

23:02.903 --> 23:05.645
we're never gonna have
herd immunity,

23:05.688 --> 23:09.910
we're never gonna be safe
until everyone is vaccinated.

23:09.953 --> 23:11.564
- But I'm not part of a herd.

23:11.607 --> 23:12.869
I'm an individual

23:12.913 --> 23:14.523
allowed to make
individual decisions

23:14.567 --> 23:16.264
for my own health care.

23:16.307 --> 23:19.572
- But you were also a soldier,

23:19.615 --> 23:20.964
part of a unit.

23:21.008 --> 23:22.488
You fought alongside
other people whose beliefs

23:22.531 --> 23:24.533
and opinions may have
been different than yours,

23:24.577 --> 23:25.752
but you fought as one.

23:25.795 --> 23:27.449
That's all
I'm asking you to do.

23:27.493 --> 23:29.973
I have 1,000 vaccines
ready to go

23:30.017 --> 23:31.453
and only one hour
to deliver them

23:31.497 --> 23:35.892
to I don't know who,
so I'm asking you, please,

23:35.936 --> 23:37.764
to round up as many holdouts
as you can

23:37.807 --> 23:39.069
and meet me
in the conference room.

23:39.113 --> 23:41.768
I'm asking you
to fight with me...

23:41.811 --> 23:43.465
[tender music]

23:43.509 --> 23:45.859
So we can try to get back
some of what we lost.

23:45.902 --> 23:50.864
♪

23:50.907 --> 23:52.256
[plucky music]

23:52.300 --> 23:54.476
- I have been looking
all over for you.

23:54.520 --> 23:56.957
Casey, what the hell
is going on?

23:57.000 --> 23:58.785
- What's going on
is that I was right.

23:58.828 --> 24:02.963
Mr. Osheyevsky is a spy.
Well, was a spy.

24:04.312 --> 24:07.228
- You're serious?
- And not just a regular spy.

24:07.271 --> 24:10.840
I'm talking, like,
a KGB double agent for the CIA.

24:12.363 --> 24:14.496
It's the best day of my life.

24:15.889 --> 24:18.935
- Could you,
uh, give us a minute?

24:18.979 --> 24:20.197
- Oh, for sure.

24:20.241 --> 24:21.764
[whispering]
I'll be the lookout.

24:21.808 --> 24:26.421
♪

24:29.468 --> 24:31.165
- KGB, huh?

24:32.558 --> 24:34.690
The dioxin was yours.

24:34.734 --> 24:37.650
[soft dramatic music]

24:37.693 --> 24:38.999
♪

24:39.042 --> 24:40.348
- I would rather die

24:40.391 --> 24:42.916
than be sent to some home
like my son wants.

24:42.959 --> 24:45.919
♪

24:45.962 --> 24:48.530
I am nothing
but a burden to him.

24:50.445 --> 24:55.058
- Is it possible
that he feels that way

24:55.102 --> 24:57.452
because he never really knew
who you were?

24:57.496 --> 25:00.542
- It was my job
to keep secrets.

25:00.586 --> 25:01.674
- I understand...

25:01.717 --> 25:03.545
♪

25:03.589 --> 25:05.547
But is it still?

25:05.591 --> 25:09.856
♪

25:09.899 --> 25:11.466
[monitor beeping rapidly]

25:11.510 --> 25:12.815
- Dr. Reynolds?

25:12.859 --> 25:15.035
- Where are we?
- She's in respiratory arrest.

25:15.078 --> 25:16.427
[dramatic music]

25:16.471 --> 25:19.387
- O2 stats are down to 84.
- I'm gonna intubate.

25:19.430 --> 25:21.868
- Prepping intubation kit now.
- Oh, baby.

25:21.911 --> 25:23.957
I don't know what's happening.

25:24.000 --> 25:25.741
Your body's
not rejecting your heart.

25:25.785 --> 25:27.134
- No, just everything else.

25:27.177 --> 25:28.788
♪

25:28.831 --> 25:30.180
Floyd.

25:31.312 --> 25:34.097
Her blood type,
you said it was AB.

25:36.665 --> 25:38.580
- Guys, think back
to four or five weeks ago.

25:38.624 --> 25:40.060
Did Kiri get sick or--

25:40.103 --> 25:42.062
- I don't think so.
- No, she had that stomachache.

25:42.105 --> 25:44.064
About a month ago,
but it wasn't--

25:44.107 --> 25:45.718
- Lisa, get me tacrolimus
and methotrexate.

25:45.761 --> 25:47.241
- What's happening?

25:47.284 --> 25:49.896
- Hopefully Kiri's more
extraordinary than I thought.

25:49.939 --> 25:52.812
♪

25:52.855 --> 25:54.509
Okay, what do you see?

25:54.553 --> 25:56.946
- Okay, it looks
like she had E. coli,

25:56.990 --> 25:58.948
but this complication
is so rare...

25:58.992 --> 26:00.733
- But?
- We were right.

26:00.776 --> 26:02.212
Her blood type's changed.

26:02.256 --> 26:03.910
- She's not AB anymore.
- Nope.

26:03.953 --> 26:06.303
She is type O,
same as her new heart.

26:06.347 --> 26:07.696
- Which explains why
her body's rejecting

26:07.740 --> 26:10.917
everything but the heart,
so if I bombard her

26:10.960 --> 26:12.788
with immunosuppressants--

26:12.832 --> 26:14.268
- [chuckles]
Go!

26:14.311 --> 26:15.748
Go take care of our girl.

26:15.791 --> 26:18.751
[soft dramatic music]

26:18.794 --> 26:22.145
♪

26:22.189 --> 26:25.627
- Max?
- Todd?

26:25.671 --> 26:28.848
♪

26:28.891 --> 26:30.197
Come in.

26:30.240 --> 26:32.591
Wow, everybody, come on in.

26:32.634 --> 26:34.810
Uh, you can
get set up right here.

26:34.854 --> 26:37.900
Thank you all for coming.
But seriously, thank you.

26:37.944 --> 26:39.293
- You're welcome.

26:39.336 --> 26:41.425
- Uh, okay, everyone just--
let's form a line,

26:41.469 --> 26:43.384
and we'll be with you
in one second.

26:43.427 --> 26:46.517
Thank you so much.
Okay, we're gonna do this.

26:46.561 --> 26:49.782
Okay, there we go.

26:49.825 --> 26:51.653
♪

26:51.697 --> 26:54.438
Um, you're the man, Todd.

26:54.482 --> 26:56.310
You'll just feel
a little pinch.

26:56.353 --> 26:57.877
[watch beeping]
- Max?

26:57.920 --> 27:02.577
- Yeah.

27:02.621 --> 27:05.014
Don't say it.
- Max, I'm sorry, but--

27:05.058 --> 27:08.452
- [sighs]
- Max?

27:09.540 --> 27:11.934
- I'm sorry, sir.
We're too late.

27:11.978 --> 27:13.501
- I don't understand.

27:13.544 --> 27:15.851
These vaccines have expired.
They're no good anymore.

27:15.895 --> 27:17.374
- Just now?

27:17.418 --> 27:19.072
But a minute can't
make a difference, can it?

27:19.115 --> 27:22.684
- There are regulations.
- I'm sorry, Todd.

27:22.728 --> 27:25.644
♪

27:25.687 --> 27:28.821
Sorry, everyone.
We're out of time.

27:28.864 --> 27:35.741
♪

27:47.404 --> 27:49.842
- His name was Tobias.

27:49.885 --> 27:51.495
Toby.

27:51.539 --> 27:53.280
He was two years
younger than me.

27:53.323 --> 27:55.195
He was definitely the favorite.

27:55.238 --> 28:00.069
He was handsome,
confident, skinny.

28:02.506 --> 28:05.031
I was...

28:05.074 --> 28:06.641
I was me.

28:06.685 --> 28:08.077
♪

28:08.121 --> 28:10.384
I could have cured cancer,

28:10.427 --> 28:12.560
and it wouldn't have been
enough for our old man.

28:14.301 --> 28:18.261
But Toby,
oh, Toby could do no wrong.

28:18.305 --> 28:19.698
He was a golden boy.

28:21.090 --> 28:23.571
So it was prom night,

28:23.614 --> 28:26.530
um, senior year.

28:27.618 --> 28:29.620
And Toby
was with Jenny Harmeyer,

28:29.664 --> 28:32.841
queen of the cool kids,
and he'd rented a tux

28:32.885 --> 28:36.192
and a limo and the whole show.

28:41.110 --> 28:43.243
Um, I was up watching TV

28:43.286 --> 28:46.463
when they came home late,
drunk.

28:47.813 --> 28:51.817
They were kissing
and laughing and teasing me.

28:53.340 --> 28:55.385
Making fun of the fat brother.

28:58.127 --> 29:01.827
I just--
I hated the way he treated me,

29:01.870 --> 29:04.743
especially in front
of other people,

29:04.786 --> 29:06.179
in front of Jenny.

29:06.222 --> 29:10.618
♪

29:10.661 --> 29:12.968
So that night...

29:13.012 --> 29:15.188
I'd had enough, you know?

29:15.231 --> 29:17.320
♪

29:17.364 --> 29:21.324
I called out
to our parents upstairs

29:21.368 --> 29:23.283
to wake 'em up,

29:23.326 --> 29:25.372
knowing that he would be busted
for drinking.

29:28.375 --> 29:30.594
He was so pissed,
but what could he do?

29:30.638 --> 29:34.120
He just--he snatched up
our mom's keys off the table,

29:34.163 --> 29:36.731
and they went back out again.

29:36.775 --> 29:39.473
♪

29:39.516 --> 29:42.824
Made it about two blocks
before he broadsided a truck.

29:42.868 --> 29:45.696
♪

29:45.740 --> 29:47.655
No seat belts.

29:47.698 --> 29:50.092
They both
went through the windshield.

29:50.136 --> 29:53.008
Jenny lived, and Toby died
on the way to the hospital.

29:53.052 --> 29:55.576
♪

29:55.619 --> 29:57.186
- Iggy!

29:58.579 --> 30:01.843
Oh, I'm gonna go get the kids.
You want anything?

30:01.887 --> 30:03.236
- Uh...

30:03.279 --> 30:06.717
[tense music]

30:06.761 --> 30:08.719
Yeah, some soup.

30:08.763 --> 30:09.982
- Sure, what kind?

30:10.025 --> 30:12.680
♪

30:12.723 --> 30:14.551
- Lentil...

30:14.595 --> 30:17.728
from that little place I like
on 9th and 11th.

30:17.772 --> 30:21.341
♪

30:21.384 --> 30:23.996
- You got it.
Okay.

30:24.039 --> 30:26.868
♪

30:26.912 --> 30:28.391
- [sighs]

30:29.436 --> 30:31.612
- You could have
told him I was here.

30:33.222 --> 30:34.745
- How would that have helped?

30:36.443 --> 30:38.445
I want to help you.

30:38.488 --> 30:42.231
♪

30:44.494 --> 30:44.843
.

30:44.886 --> 30:46.540
- Tomorrow afternoon,

30:46.583 --> 30:47.671
I'm gonna go
down to the courthouse,

30:47.715 --> 30:49.325
and I'm gonna get this revoked,

30:49.369 --> 30:51.762
but you have
to promise me one thing.

30:53.112 --> 30:55.331
I need you to meet me
at my office tomorrow

30:55.375 --> 30:57.986
at 3:00 p.m. sharp...

30:58.030 --> 30:59.074
and we're gonna pick up
your treatment

30:59.118 --> 31:00.467
exactly where we left off.

31:02.425 --> 31:04.427
- Are you gonna tell anyone
I was here?

31:05.385 --> 31:07.169
- No.

31:07.213 --> 31:09.824
- Not even Martin?
- No, not even Martin.

31:11.043 --> 31:13.872
This is between me
and you, okay?

31:13.915 --> 31:16.831
[soft dramatic music]

31:16.875 --> 31:19.399
♪

31:19.442 --> 31:21.705
- Thank you, Dr. Frome.

31:22.750 --> 31:26.797
- Now, go before my family
gets back with my soup.

31:26.841 --> 31:33.848
♪

31:33.892 --> 31:36.807
[dramatic music]

31:36.851 --> 31:39.027
♪

31:39.071 --> 31:40.942
[tires screeching]

31:40.986 --> 31:42.204
[siren wails]

31:42.248 --> 31:43.858
- Stop right there!
Don't move!

31:43.902 --> 31:50.082
♪

31:50.125 --> 31:52.954
Listen, don't move.

31:52.998 --> 31:54.825
- Iggy?
Iggy!

31:54.869 --> 31:57.045
♪

31:57.089 --> 31:59.265
I got you.
I got you.

31:59.308 --> 32:01.963
- [sobbing]
- You're okay.

32:02.007 --> 32:04.139
♪

32:04.183 --> 32:05.749
I got you.
I got you.

32:05.793 --> 32:07.926
[sighs]

32:07.969 --> 32:10.841
♪

32:10.885 --> 32:13.932
- [laughs]
Dada.

32:13.975 --> 32:16.412
Dada!
Dada, hi.

32:16.456 --> 32:18.110
Hi, Dada.

32:18.153 --> 32:20.329
Hi.

32:20.373 --> 32:21.678
Dada, hi.

32:22.462 --> 32:24.203
- Thought I might
find you up here.

32:26.031 --> 32:29.034
- Dada.
Dada.

32:31.340 --> 32:34.430
Dada, hi.
- [chuckles]

32:34.474 --> 32:36.867
- Dada!

32:45.876 --> 32:48.444
- Max...

32:48.488 --> 32:49.924
do you want some advice?

32:51.534 --> 32:52.971
- I'll take it.

32:54.885 --> 32:57.105
- You fight for her, Max.

32:59.673 --> 33:01.109
Fight for her.

33:01.153 --> 33:04.025
[Ocie Elliott's "Run To You"]

33:04.069 --> 33:06.810
♪

33:06.854 --> 33:08.508
- It feels like
all I do is fight.

33:09.857 --> 33:11.511
This morning,
I had 1,000 vaccines

33:11.554 --> 33:13.078
and a line of people
ready to take 'em,

33:13.121 --> 33:15.167
and that wasn't enough for me.

33:15.210 --> 33:17.212
I wanted to aim higher,
do better,

33:17.256 --> 33:21.390
so because I was stupid...

33:23.088 --> 33:24.045
Nobody got 'em.

33:24.089 --> 33:26.961
♪

33:27.005 --> 33:29.529
Because I had to fight.

33:29.572 --> 33:31.531
- [chuckles]

33:34.099 --> 33:38.538
- That wasn't really
a punch line.

33:41.410 --> 33:44.892
- When have you ever not wanted
all of us to aim higher?

33:46.720 --> 33:48.939
To fight?

33:48.983 --> 33:50.898
It's all a fight.

33:52.987 --> 33:57.209
Luna, Mina...

33:57.252 --> 33:59.080
vaccines, this hospital...

33:59.124 --> 34:01.822
♪

34:01.865 --> 34:03.215
Us.

34:04.390 --> 34:08.872
- ♪ And I'll run to you
when the waters rise ♪

34:08.916 --> 34:10.874
- If you don't have
to fight for it,

34:10.918 --> 34:12.528
it's 'cause it's not worth it.

34:12.572 --> 34:16.402
- ♪ Run to you
if bombs ignite ♪

34:16.445 --> 34:17.316
♪

34:17.359 --> 34:20.101
♪ I'll still call to you

34:20.145 --> 34:22.886
♪ If I lose my sight

34:22.930 --> 34:24.366
♪

34:24.410 --> 34:29.023
♪ And I'll fall for you
if you need a fight ♪

34:29.067 --> 34:32.983
♪

34:33.027 --> 34:35.508
♪ Using all that we can

34:35.551 --> 34:39.512
♪

34:39.555 --> 34:42.428
♪ Dominating all the land

34:42.471 --> 34:46.301
♪

34:46.345 --> 34:48.608
♪ Terrified it's gonna end

34:48.651 --> 34:53.917
♪

34:53.961 --> 34:56.050
- Wow.
- Good start.

34:56.094 --> 34:57.138
- [chuckles]

34:57.182 --> 34:58.748
♪

34:58.792 --> 35:01.099
- ♪ Don't know
what it's all for ♪

35:01.142 --> 35:05.364
♪

35:05.407 --> 35:07.757
♪ Don't want it anymore

35:07.801 --> 35:10.020
♪

35:10.064 --> 35:12.414
♪ And I'll run to you

35:12.458 --> 35:15.156
♪ When the waters rise

35:15.200 --> 35:18.377
- Mm.
[breathes deeply]

35:18.420 --> 35:20.857
Mm.
- Want to take it slow?

35:20.901 --> 35:22.990
- Nah.

35:23.033 --> 35:25.949
I want to take you
right here.

35:25.993 --> 35:29.039
- ♪ If I lose my sight

35:29.083 --> 35:30.954
- But knowing
you're with another man--

35:30.998 --> 35:33.479
- ♪ I'll fall for you

35:33.522 --> 35:35.133
I don't know.

35:35.176 --> 35:37.570
Maybe the type of relationship
I want doesn't exist anymore.

35:37.613 --> 35:39.267
Maybe it never did.

35:39.311 --> 35:42.183
- ♪ Using all that we can

35:42.227 --> 35:43.619
- And even though my body

35:43.663 --> 35:46.622
is telling me
to just let go and jump...

35:46.666 --> 35:48.842
- ♪ Dominating all the land

35:48.885 --> 35:51.845
♪

35:51.888 --> 35:53.107
- ♪ Terrified

35:53.151 --> 35:54.935
- I can't.

35:54.978 --> 35:58.678
♪

35:58.721 --> 36:01.289
- ♪ How do we
come back again ♪

36:01.333 --> 36:04.336
♪

36:04.379 --> 36:08.992
♪ And we know
the whole while ♪

36:09.036 --> 36:10.733
♪ All that's good

36:10.777 --> 36:17.610
♪

36:17.653 --> 36:22.354
♪ All our past problems

36:22.397 --> 36:24.834
♪ Understood

36:24.878 --> 36:26.227
♪

36:26.271 --> 36:28.098
- You were right.

36:30.100 --> 36:33.713
We don't know each other,
and that's on me.

36:37.107 --> 36:39.980
I keep hammering on
at you to open up,

36:40.023 --> 36:42.548
but that has to go both ways.

36:42.591 --> 36:44.245
♪

36:44.289 --> 36:47.683
- ♪ We would come to know

36:47.727 --> 36:49.294
♪

36:49.337 --> 36:52.645
♪ Our falsehood

36:52.688 --> 36:55.517
♪

36:55.561 --> 36:57.998
- I don't like
talking about myself.

36:58.041 --> 37:01.349
- ♪ When the waters rise

37:01.393 --> 37:04.178
- Especially about...

37:04.222 --> 37:05.745
about painful things.

37:08.095 --> 37:10.184
But that can
leave me quite alone.

37:12.839 --> 37:15.058
Perhaps you're
a little like that too?

37:15.102 --> 37:18.236
- ♪ And I'll fall for you

37:18.279 --> 37:20.150
♪ If you need a fight

37:20.194 --> 37:22.196
♪

37:22.240 --> 37:24.894
♪ And I'll run to you

37:24.938 --> 37:28.681
♪ When the waters rise

37:28.724 --> 37:31.379
- That's your grandfather.
My father.

37:31.423 --> 37:33.512
- ♪ If bombs ignite

37:33.555 --> 37:35.992
- And he died
when you were three.

37:36.036 --> 37:38.299
- ♪ I'll still call to you

37:38.343 --> 37:41.955
♪ If I do go blind

37:41.998 --> 37:44.610
♪ And I'll be all for you

37:44.653 --> 37:48.135
♪ If you lose the fight

37:49.702 --> 37:51.138
- When did you know?

37:53.314 --> 37:56.578
- Well, you hate lentil soup,

37:56.622 --> 37:59.712
and you used the safe word
from my practice.

37:59.755 --> 38:02.584
- 9th and 11th.
- 911, not too subtle.

38:07.372 --> 38:09.983
How did you...

38:10.026 --> 38:12.899
keep him calm,
from hurting you?

38:12.942 --> 38:15.423
- I told him about my brother.

38:15.467 --> 38:18.296
- What, how he died in Iraq?

38:18.339 --> 38:21.299
[soft dramatic music]

38:21.342 --> 38:24.606
- I gave Chance...

38:24.650 --> 38:27.000
everything.

38:27.043 --> 38:28.784
I gave him every part of me.

38:28.828 --> 38:32.310
♪

38:32.353 --> 38:34.921
I just wanted him
to get better,

38:34.964 --> 38:36.792
but it was never enough.

38:36.836 --> 38:40.970
♪

38:41.014 --> 38:42.624
So I made up a story.

38:42.668 --> 38:46.628
♪

38:46.672 --> 38:48.804
I lied,

38:48.848 --> 38:50.806
and it worked.

38:50.850 --> 38:55.245
♪

38:55.289 --> 38:57.683
I don't know
what that says about me.

38:59.424 --> 39:02.992
I don't know what that says
about me as a human being

39:03.036 --> 39:04.994
or as a therapist.

39:05.038 --> 39:07.997
♪

39:08.041 --> 39:09.347
I don't know.

39:10.913 --> 39:13.438
- It says you finally
put yourself first...

39:15.440 --> 39:17.267
And that's a good thing.

39:17.311 --> 39:24.362
♪

39:36.896 --> 39:38.724
- I'm an addict.

39:39.942 --> 39:44.207
I mean, I'm in recovery...

39:44.251 --> 39:46.514
but I'm always
gonna be an addict.

39:48.647 --> 39:50.257
- I know.

39:51.389 --> 39:54.479
- I, uh--I've been
with women before,

39:54.522 --> 39:57.177
like, a few times,

39:57.220 --> 39:58.744
never in a relationship.

40:01.268 --> 40:03.096
- I know that too.

40:03.139 --> 40:06.839
- I can't cook, like, at all.

40:06.882 --> 40:09.145
I mean, like, I would burn
this entire place down

40:09.189 --> 40:10.451
if I even tried.

40:11.670 --> 40:14.673
- That, I kind of guessed.

40:15.717 --> 40:19.895
- I don't want there to be
any secrets between us.

40:19.939 --> 40:22.550
- I think I know everything.
- You don't.

40:23.856 --> 40:27.729
The thing is, I wish I--

40:27.773 --> 40:29.644
[sighs]

40:29.688 --> 40:34.257
I never told you before...

40:34.301 --> 40:38.174
♪

40:38.218 --> 40:40.742
I love you.

40:40.786 --> 40:47.706
♪

41:01.502 --> 41:03.025
- Max, what are you doing here?

41:03.069 --> 41:05.854
- I thought to call,
but then I realized

41:05.898 --> 41:07.900
what I had to say
needed to be said in person.

41:09.641 --> 41:12.470
Everything that you said
this morning is true.

41:12.513 --> 41:14.907
I'm not a perfect father,
and I never will be,

41:14.950 --> 41:17.213
but I am a good father...
- Max--

41:17.257 --> 41:19.868
- And I will be better tomorrow
and the day after that,

41:19.912 --> 41:21.479
and you know who loved
that part of me

41:21.522 --> 41:23.916
more than anyone?
It was your daughter.

41:23.959 --> 41:27.354
And I get the pain
of losing her.

41:27.397 --> 41:29.878
I really do,

41:29.922 --> 41:32.794
but she would never want Luna
to be without her dad.

41:34.056 --> 41:37.930
If you want to go to court,
we can,

41:37.973 --> 41:39.627
but you'll lose.

41:40.585 --> 41:41.760
And when that happens,

41:41.803 --> 41:42.978
I will walk
out of that courtroom,

41:43.022 --> 41:44.676
and you will
never see Luna again.

41:46.416 --> 41:49.289
And I don't want that...

41:49.332 --> 41:53.293
for Luna, for you...

41:53.336 --> 41:54.599
for Georgia...

41:54.642 --> 41:56.514
[tender music]

41:56.557 --> 42:00.039
Because she knew so clearly...

42:00.082 --> 42:01.562
what you clearly don't.

42:01.606 --> 42:04.260
♪

42:04.304 --> 42:06.959
And that is that I will never
stop fighting for my daughter.

42:07.002 --> 42:09.439
I will fight for her
until the day I die...

42:09.483 --> 42:13.531
♪

42:13.574 --> 42:15.184
And I'm here to take her home.

42:15.228 --> 42:18.884
♪
